      {/* Differences from the Official Spec */}
      <section id="spec-differences" class="mb-14 scroll-mt-20">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Differences from the Official Spec</h2>
        <div class="space-y-4 text-sm leading-relaxed">
          <p class="text-muted-foreground">
            We compared the GlideComp scoring engine line-by-line against the FAI Sporting Code
            Section 7F (2024 edition). Beyond the unimplemented features listed above, these are
            the places where GlideComp's behaviour differs from the letter of the spec. Section
            numbers (§) refer to the 2024 edition and link to the relevant page of the
            <SpecRef section="0" label="official PDF" />.
          </p>

          <div class="space-y-4 ml-2">
            <div>
              <h3 class="text-base font-semibold mb-1">Start gates: placeholder midnight gates are ignored (<SpecRef section="6.3.3" />)</h3>
              <p class="text-muted-foreground">
                GlideComp scores race-to-goal start gates per the spec: each pilot's start time is
                the last gate at or before their start-cylinder crossing (<SpecRef section="8.3.1" />), crossings
                before the first gate cannot validate a start (<SpecRef section="8.3" />), early starts follow the
                <SpecRef section="12.2" label="§12.2" /> rules (paragliders scored launch→start; hang gliders get the jump-the-gun
                penalty), and the leading-coefficient clock runs from the first gate (<SpecRef section="11.3.1" />).
                One pragmatic deviation: a race task whose <em>only</em> gate is exactly 00:00:00
                UTC is treated as having no gates and timed as elapsed time — some tools write
                that lone midnight gate as a placeholder to satisfy the file format's
                non-empty-gates rule, and a real midnight-UTC gate does not occur in practice.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h3 class="text-base font-semibold mb-1">Hang gliding "best time" follows AirScore, not the letter of §11.2.1 (<SpecRef section="11.2" />, <SpecRef section="12.1" />)</h3>
              <p class="text-muted-foreground">
                The ESS-but-not-goal rule itself is implemented per <SpecRef section="12.1" label="§12.1" />:
                paragliders lose all time points without goal, and hang glider pilots keep 80% of
                their time and arrival points by default (configurable per competition). However,
                §11.2.1 defines "best time" as the fastest pilot <em>who also reached goal</em>,
                and GlideComp instead mirrors AirScore's implementation: while the
                ESS-but-not-goal share keeps part of the time points (the HG default), the best
                time is the fastest pilot to reach ESS, goal or not — so the docked pilots' speed
                fractions are measured on the same scale as everyone else's. When the share is
                set to 0% (always the case for paragliding), the best time is goal-validated
                exactly as the spec reads.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h3 class="text-base font-semibold mb-1">Older paragliding comps keep the GAP2020 leading weight (<SpecRef section="10" />)</h3>
              <p class="text-muted-foreground">
                The 2024 spec derives the PG leading weight from a per-task
                <em>LeadingTimeRatio</em> parameter (default 26% of the non-distance weight, and
                100% of it when nobody makes goal). Paragliding competitions created from
                <strong>15 July 2026</strong> onward <strong>default</strong> to this
                <strong>S7F 2024</strong> formula. Competitions created before that date keep the
                earlier <strong>GAP2020</strong> formula — 35% of the non-distance weight when
                someone makes goal, and
                <Fragment set:html={km(String.raw`0.1 \times \text{BestDist}/\text{TaskDist}`)} /> when nobody does —
                so their published scores never shift; this matches AirScore's gap2020/gap2021
                presets. Either comp can switch between the two (and set its LeadingTimeRatio) under
                <em>Paragliding leading weight</em> in scoring settings. The hang-gliding weights
                match the 2024 spec and are unaffected by this setting.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h3 class="text-base font-semibold mb-1">Line control zones are only supported at goal (<SpecRef section="8.4" />)</h3>
              <p class="text-muted-foreground">
                A goal line is scored as the spec defines it — a line through the goal waypoint,
                perpendicular to the final leg, with the semi-circular control zone behind it —
                but goal is the only place GlideComp understands a line. The spec also allows an
                intermediate turnpoint to be a line, validated when two consecutive fixes sit on
                opposite sides of it and going around its end would have required an implausible
                speed (over 120&nbsp;km/h). GlideComp treats every turnpoint before goal as a
                cylinder. Line-type turnpoints are rare in XCTrack task files, so in practice this
                affects few tasks.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h3 class="text-base font-semibold mb-1">Launch window: only provable violations are enforced (<SpecRef section="8.6.1" />)</h3>
              <p class="text-muted-foreground">
                The spec counts a pilot's turnpoints only if they launched within the launch time
                window. GlideComp enforces the half of this that a tracklog can prove: a
                start-cylinder crossing recorded <em>before</em> the window even opened
                (<code>takeoff.timeOpen</code> in the task file) means the pilot was airborne
                before launching was allowed, so such crossings cannot validate a start — the
                score explanation says so. What a tracklog alone cannot prove is <em>when</em> the
                pilot launched: a pilot who launched before the window but only started the course
                after it opened, or who launched after the window closed, is not detected —
                launch-time detection is not part of scoring, so those cases are left to the
                scorekeeper (a penalty can be applied manually).
              </p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h3 class="text-base font-semibold mb-1">Smaller details</h3>
              <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-muted-foreground space-y-2 ml-2">
                <li>
                  <strong>Cylinder tolerance default (<SpecRef section="8.1" />):</strong> GlideComp applies the full
                  spec tolerance band — a percentage plus a 5&nbsp;m absolute minimum, extending
                  outward for cylinders you enter and inward for the start you exit. The default
                  percentage is 0.5% (the Cat&nbsp;2 maximum), used for every competition rather
                  than auto-selecting 0.1% for Cat&nbsp;1 events; it is configurable per task. A
                  goal line carries no tolerance band — it is scored as exact geometry.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Mis-set task deadlines are ignored (<SpecRef section="8.3" />):</strong> the goal
                  deadline is enforced as the spec requires — crossings after it don't count, and
                  a landed-out pilot's distance is measured only up to it (<SpecRef section="11.1" />) — with one
                  pragmatic guard: a deadline that falls at or before the first start gate (or a
                  launch-window open time at or after the deadline) is a task-setting mistake that
                  would zero every pilot, so it is treated as unset, in the same spirit as the
                  missing-SSS/ESS fallbacks. When the deadline shaped a pilot's score, the score
                  explanation shows the cutoff time and each ignored crossing.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Rounding (<SpecRef section="11" />, <SpecRef section="12.4" />):</strong> GlideComp rounds each pilot's total to
                  one decimal place, after subtracting any penalties, exactly as the 2024 spec
                  requires. Component points are likewise kept to 0.1. The scoreboard displays
                  totals as whole points for readability, but ranking and tie-breaks use the
                  one-decimal value.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Optional leading/arrival points:</strong> the spec always allocates
                  leading weight (and arrival weight in hang gliding classes 1 and 5). GlideComp
                  defaults to the FAI formula (leading on for both categories, arrival on for hang
                  gliding) but lets a competition switch either off — common in club-level scoring,
                  though itself a departure from the spec when disabled.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Distance origin:</strong> the optional
                  <a href="#distance-origin" class="underline hover:text-foreground">"start cylinder" distance origin</a>
                  deliberately deviates from the spec's launch-to-goal task distance (<SpecRef section="6.4.2" />) to
                  match some national (e.g. HGFA/SAFA) rule wording. The default "take-off"
                  setting follows the spec.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Distance precision:</strong> distances are computed on the WGS84
                  ellipsoid as the spec requires (<SpecRef section="4.2" />), but the optimized route isn't
                  bit-identical to other tools such as
                  <a href="https://airscore.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="underline hover:text-foreground">AirScore</a>,
                  so landed-out pilots' point values can differ slightly. This affects absolute
                  values more than relative ranking.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p class="text-muted-foreground">
            If any of these matter for your competition, or you spot a difference not listed here,
            please
            <a href="https://github.com/pokle/glidecomp/issues" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="underline hover:text-foreground">
              open an issue on GitHub
            </a>
            — scoring transparency is the point of this project.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

